Comment (src/components/system-security-plans/SystemImplementationComponentCreateForm.vue:81):
**[Medium] The `FormInput`/`FormTextarea` → volt swap silently dropped `w-full`, breaking layout in every converted form.**

The legacy components bake `w-full` into their root class. The volt `InputText`/`Textarea` are only full-width under `p-fluid:w-full` (i.e. with the `fluid` prop), which none of these call sites set. Verified in the running app: in the Create Component dialog, Type / Title / Description / Purpose / Remarks render as tiny shrunken boxes with their labels squished beside them instead of above — screenshot-confirmed; the UUID field only survives because its surrounding flex container gives it `flex-1`.

This affects **all 13 swapped form components in this PR** wherever the input doesn't happen to get width from a parent flex/grid: both component forms, both user forms, both leveraged-auth forms, both inventory-item forms, both statement forms, both implemented-requirement forms, `ByComponentEditForm`, `ControlImplementationEditForm`, and `SystemImplementationOverviewForm`.

Suggested fix: add `class="w-full"` (or `fluid`) at each swapped call site — or, much less invasively, do a pass over the converted forms and verify each renders like its `main` counterpart. The unit tests can't catch this (stubs don't carry the volt classes), so a quick visual sweep of each dialog is the verification that matters here.
